Welcome to the=C2=A0408=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined u=
s since last week! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0216,703 sma=
rt, curious folks by subscribing here:
The sourcing tool for data driven VCs
Harmonic AI  [ https://substack.com/redirect/61434403-3320-46a3-ba51-14963a=
a03bfb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
is the startup discovery tool trusted by VCs and sales teams in search of b=
reakout companies. It=E2=80=99s like if Crunchbase or CB Insights was built=
 today and without a bunch of punitive paywalls. Accel, YC, Brex and hundre=
ds more use Harmonic to:
Discover new startups in any sector, geography, or stage including stealth.
Track companies=E2=80=99 performance with insights on fundraising, hiring, =
web traffic, and more.
Monitor their networks for the next generation of founders.
Whether you're an investor or GTM leader, Harmonic is just one of those hig=
h-ROI no-brainers to have in your stack.=C2=A0
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B ,=20
Happy Tuesday! Hope you all had a great Thanksgiving (or enjoyed the peace =
and quiet while us Americans were in Turkey comas).=20
Apologies that this is a little late =E2=80=94 once again, the newsletter g=
ods dropped a perfect example [ https://substack.com/redirect/28d1c12d-9bf4=
-4e9d-a01f-c31bb1c60deb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] of the point I was trying to make in my lap at the last m=
inute, and I=E2=80=99ve been up since 5:30 trying to incorporate it.=20
We live in a time of extreme narratives. It=E2=80=99s easy to get caught up=
 and worked up when you take the extremes in isolation. Don=E2=80=99t. They=
=E2=80=99re part of a bigger game, and once you see it, the world makes a l=
ot more sense.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
Narrative Tug-of-War
One of the biggest changes to how I see the world over the past year or so =
is viewing ideological debates as games of narrative tug-of-war.=C2=A0
For every narrative, there is an equal and opposite narrative. It=E2=80=99s=
 practically predetermined, cultural physics.=C2=A0
One side pulls hard to its extreme, and the other pulls back to its own.=C2=
=A0
AI is going to kill us all =E2=86=90=E2=86=92 AI is going to save the world=
=2E=C2=A0
What starts as a minor disagreement gets amplified into completely opposing=
 worldviews. What starts as a nuanced conversation gets boiled down to catc=
hphrases. Those who start as your opponents become your enemies.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s easy to get worked up if you focus on the extremes, on the tea=
ms tugging the rope on each side. It=E2=80=99s certainly easy to nitpick ev=
erything they say and point out all of the things they missed or left out.=
=C2=A0
Don=E2=80=99t. Focus on the knot in the middle.=C2=A0
That knot, moving back and forth over the center line as each team tries to=
 pull it further to their own side, is the important thing to watch. That=
=E2=80=99s the emergent synthesis of the ideas, and where they translate in=
to policy and action.=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s this concept called the Overton Window: the range of polici=
es or ideas that are politically acceptable at any given time.=C2=A0
Since Joseph Overton came up with the idea in the mid-1990s, the concept ha=
s expanded beyond government policy. Now, it=E2=80=99s used to describe how=
 ideas enter the mainstream conversation where they influence public opinio=
n, societal norms, and institutional practices.=C2=A0
The Overton Window is the knot in the narrative tug-of-war. The teams pulli=
ng on either side don=E2=80=99t actually expect that everyone will agree wi=
th and adopt their ideas; they just need to pull hard enough that the Overt=
on Window shifts in their direction.=C2=A0
Another way to think about it is like price anchoring, when a company offer=
s multiple price tiers knowing that you=E2=80=99ll land on the one in the m=
iddle and pay more for it than you would have without seeing how little you=
 get for the lower price or how much you=E2=80=99d have to pay to get all o=
f the features.=C2=A0
No one expects you to pay $7,000 for the Super Pro tier (although they=E2=
=80=99d be happy if you did). They just know that by showing it to you, it =
will make paying $69 for the Pro tier more palatable.=C2=A0
The same thing happens with narratives, but instead of one company carefull=
y setting prices to maximize the likelihood that you buy the Pro tier, inde=
pendent and opposed teams, often made up of people who=E2=80=99ve never met=
, loosely coordinated through group chats and memes, somehow figure out how=
 to pull hard enough that they move the knot back to what they view as an a=
cceptable place. It=E2=80=99s a kind of cultural magic when you think about=
 it.=C2=A0
There are a lot of examples I could use to illustrate the idea, many of whi=
ch could get me in trouble, so I=E2=80=99ll stick to what I know: tech. Spe=
cifically, degrowth vs. growth, or EA vs. e/acc.=C2=A0
EA vs. e/acc
One of the biggest debates in my corner of Twitter, which burst out into th=
e world with this month=E2=80=99s OpenAI drama, is Effective Altruism (EA) =
vs. Effective Accelerationism (e/acc).=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s the latest manifestation of an age-old struggle between those =
who believe we should grow, and those who don=E2=80=99t, and the perfect ca=
se study through which to explore the narrative tug-of-war.=C2=A0
If you look at either side in isolation, both views seem extreme.=C2=A0
EA (which I=E2=80=99m using as a shorthand for the AI-risk team), believes =
that there is a very good chance that AI is going to kill all of us. Given =
the fact that there will be trillions of humans in the coming millennia, ev=
en if there=E2=80=99s a 1% chance AI will kill us all, preventing that from=
 happening will save tens or hundreds of billions of expected lives. We nee=
d to stop AI development before we get to AGI, whatever the cost.=C2=A0
As that team=E2=80=99s captain, Eliezer Yudkowsky, wrote in  [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/3cff496a-c27e-4b62-b288-433fca74ac1d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]Time [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/3cff496a-c27e-4b62-b288-433fca74ac1d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:
Shut down all the large GPU clusters (the large computer farms where the mo=
st powerful AIs are refined). Shut down all the large training runs. Put a =
ceiling on how much computing power anyone is allowed to use in training an=
 AI system, and move it downward over the coming years to compensate for mo=
re efficient training algorithms. No exceptions for governments and militar=
ies. Make immediate multinational agreements to prevent the prohibited acti=
vities from moving elsewhere. Track all GPUs sold. If intelligence says tha=
t a country outside the agreement is building a GPU cluster, be less scared=
 of a shooting conflict between nations than of the moratorium being violat=
ed; be willing to destroy a rogue datacenter by airstrike.
The idea that we should bomb datacenters to prevent the development of AI, =
taken in a vacuum, is absurd, as many of AI=E2=80=99s supporters were quick=
 to point out.=C2=A0
e/acc (which I=E2=80=99m using as a shorthand for the pro-AI team) believes=
 that AI won=E2=80=99t kill us all and that we should do whatever we can to=
 accelerate it. They believe that technology is good, capitalism is good, a=
nd that the combination of the two, the techno-capital machine, is the =E2=
=80=9Cengine of perpetual material creation, growth, and abundance. We need=
 to protect the techno-capital machine at all costs.=C2=A0
Marc Andreessen, who rocks =E2=80=9Ce/acc=E2=80=9D in his twitter bio [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/71371869-ee70-4f44-8e99-3b4eb3314b3f?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], recently wrote T=
he Techno-Optimist Manifesto [ https://substack.com/redirect/4915fae1-411b-=
43b3-b21c-ba423d37b3a0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], in which he makes the case for essentially unchecked tech=
nological progress. One section in particular drew the ire of AI=E2=80=99s =
opponents:=C2=A0
We have enemies.
Our enemies are not bad people =E2=80=93 but rather bad ideas.
Our present society has been subjected to a mass demoralization campaign fo=
r six decades =E2=80=93 against technology and against life =E2=80=93 under=
 varying names like =E2=80=9Cexistential risk=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Csustainabi=
lity=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9CESG=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9CSustainable Development Goal=
s=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Csocial responsibility=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Cstakeholder c=
apitalism=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9CPrecautionary Principle=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Ctru=
st and safety=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Ctech ethics=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Crisk manage=
ment=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Cde-growth=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Cthe limits of growth=
=E2=80=9D.
This demoralization campaign is based on bad ideas of the past =E2=80=93 zo=
mbie ideas, many derived from Communism, disastrous then and now =E2=80=93 =
that have refused to die.
The idea that things most people view as good =E2=80=93 like sustainability=
, ethics, and risk management =E2=80=93 taken in a vacuum, seems absurd, as=
 many journalists and bloggers were quick to point out.=C2=A0
What critics of both pieces either missed is that neither argument should b=
e taken in a vacuum. Nuance isn=E2=80=99t the point of any one specific arg=
ument. You pull the edges hard so that nuance can emerge in the middle.=C2=
=A0
While there are people on both teams who support their side=E2=80=99s most =
radical views =E2=80=93 a complete AI shutdown on one side, unchecked techn=
o-capital growth on the other =E2=80=93 what=E2=80=99s really happening is =
a game of narrative tug-of-war in which the knot is regulation.=C2=A0
EA would like to see AI regulated, and would like to be the ones who write =
the regulation [ https://substack.com/redirect/a169403b-4e1d-4616-bb71-61ca=
9a0d6f50?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU=
 ]. e/acc would like to see AI remain open and not controlled by any one gr=
oup, be it a government or a company.=C2=A0
One side tugs by warning that AI Will Kill Us All in order to scare the pub=
lic and the government into hasty regulation, the other side tugs back by a=
rguing that AI Will Save the World [ https://substack.com/redirect/47337de5=
-5eab-4209-8c17-d8be8ceaf2a4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to stave off regulation for long enough that people =
can experience its benefits firsthand.=C2=A0
Personally, and unsurprisingly, I=E2=80=99m on the side of the techno-optim=
ists. That doesn=E2=80=99t mean that I believe that technology is a panacea=
, or that there aren=E2=80=99t real concerns that need to be addressed.=C2=
=A0
It means that I believe that growth is better than stagnation, that problem=
s have solutions, that history shows that both technological progress and c=
apitalism have improved humans=E2=80=99 standard of living, and that bad re=
gulation is a bigger risk than no regulation.=C2=A0
While the world shifts based on narrative tug-of-wars, there is also truth,=
 or at least fact patterns. Doomers =E2=80=93 from Malthus to Ehrlich =E2=
=80=93 continue to be proven wrong, but fear sells, and as a result, the ma=
instream narrative continues to lean anti-tech. The fear is that restrictiv=
e regulation is put in place before the truth can emerge.=C2=A0
Because the thing about this game of narrative tug-of-war is that it=E2=80=
=99s not a fair one.=C2=A0
The anti-growth side needs only to pull hard and long enough to get regulat=
ion enacted. Once it=E2=80=99s in place, it=E2=80=99s hard to overturn; typ=
ically, it ratchets up. Nuclear energy is a clear example [ https://substac=
k.com/redirect/37491369-3843-485c-9cf4-02a8e321fa46?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.=
gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
If they can pull the knot over the regulation line, they win, game over.=C2=
=A0
The pro-growth side has to keep pulling for long enough for the truth to em=
erge in spite of all the messiness that comes with any new technology, for =
entrepreneurs to build products that prove out the promise, and for creativ=
e humans to devise solutions that address concerns without neutering progre=
ss.=C2=A0
They need to keep the tug-of-war going long enough for solutions to emerge =
in the middle.=C2=A0
Yesterday, Ethereum co-founder Vitalik Buterin wrote a piece called My tech=
no-optimism [ https://substack.com/redirect/28d1c12d-9bf4-4e9d-a01f-c31bb1c=
60deb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
in which he proposed one such solution: d/acc.=C2=A0
The =E2=80=9Cd,=E2=80=9D he wrote, =E2=80=9Ccan stand for many things; part=
icularly, defense, decentralization, democracy and differential.=E2=80=9D I=
t means using technology to develop AI in a way that protects against poten=
tial pitfalls and prioritizes human flourishing.=C2=A0
On one side, the AI safety movement pulls with the message: =E2=80=9Cyou sh=
ould just stop.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
On the other, e/acc says, =E2=80=9Cyou=E2=80=99re already a hero just the w=
ay you are.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Vitalik proposes d/acc as a third, middle way:=C2=A0
A d/acc message, one that says "you should build, and build profitable thin=
gs, but be much more selective and intentional in making sure you are build=
ing things that help you and humanity thrive", may be a winner.
It=E2=80=99s a synthesis, one he argues can appeal to people whatever their=
 philosophy (as long as the philosophy isn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cregulate the =
technology to smithereens=E2=80=9D):=C2=A0
Without EA and e/acc pulling on both extremes, there may not have been room=
 in the middle for Vitalik=E2=80=99s d/acc. The extremes, lacking nuance th=
emself, create the space for nuance to emerge in the middle.=C2=A0
If EA wins, and regulation halts progress or concentrates it into the hands=
 of a few companies, that room no longer exists. If the goal is to regulate=
, there=E2=80=99s no room for a solution that doesn=E2=80=99t involve regul=
ation.=C2=A0
But if the goal is human flourishing, there=E2=80=99s plenty of room for so=
lutions. Keeping that room open is the point.=C2=A0
Despite the fact that Vitalik explicitly disagrees with pieces of e/acc, bo=
th Marc Andreessen [ https://substack.com/redirect/521b3918-1183-4958-8ad2-=
ead6448693a1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ] and e/acc=E2=80=99s pseudonymous co-founder Beff Jezos [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/e2290ab3-b6ba-49d5-ba1a-8ab15f1820a8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] shared Vitalik=E2=80=99s =
post. That=E2=80=99s a hint that they=E2=80=99re less worried about their s=
olution than a good solution.=C2=A0
Whether d/acc is the answer or not, it captures the point of tugging on the=
 extremes beautifully. Only once e/acc set the outer boundary could a solut=
ion that involves merging humans and AI through Neuralinks be viewed as a s=
ensible, moderate take. Ray Kurzweil made that point a couple decades ago a=
nd has the arrows to prove it.=C2=A0
In this and other narrative tug-of-wars, the extremes serve a purpose, but =
they are not the purpose. For every EA, there is an equal and opposite e/ac=
c. As long as the game continues, solutions can emerge from that tension.=
=C2=A0
Don=E2=80=99t focus on the tuggers, focus on the knot.
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/e6a29b37-1af3-4a2b-b698-ecdf1=
85b678b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox with the =
Weekly Dose on Friday!
Thanks for reading,
Packy

